### Use negative (white) space in layouts  

White space is the gaps between elements in a design. often referred to as negative space.   

the use of white space can provide emphasis on a focal point within the design. help focus the user on an action they need to take.   
For example, think about the Google Search homepage; the search bar and Google logo are surrounded by white space. The use of white space clearly communicates the action users should take: search.   

the use of white space can help group items together, which is also known as proximity.   
When elements like buttons or text are placed close to each other on a page, users naturally group these elements together and expect them to be related.   

white space helps with readability. Leaving more white space between elements makes it easier to focus on each element.   

Having too little white space increases the chance of error.   

